United Kingdom
Similarly to the U.S., the U.K. should have been one of
the more well prepared countries for a national health
crisis. However, the bungled response by the British
government has led to far more infections and deaths
than was expected and an overload on the NHS. British
citizens getting restless for the reopening of their country
as the weather warms have flocked to outdoor spaces like
beaches and parks while the pub remains closed.

India
The COVID-19 pandemic has been growing rapidly in India
for the past few weeks and has been declared a public health
crisis, especially in crowded cities like Delhi. News outlets
have shared stories of a wedding gone lawry in India, with 80
guests getting infected and the groom, who passed from the
virus. Despite this, many messages online signal hope for
containment and solidarity with victims.

Japan
Japanese officials' fears have been growing given a sudden
uptick in infections in the country. This growth is despite the
prediction that the hot summer weather would dampen the
virus's spread. Japan is realizing that they are not quite out of
the woods yet with their containment of the disease, especially
in large metropolitan cities like Tokyo.
